ues for a historiographical shift inthe framing of the Mau Mau rebellion as a Kikuyu war. Instead, Mickie Mwanzia Koster suggests that Mau Mau was a nationalist movement, embraced by non-Kikuyu communities like the Kamba ethnic group. Incorporating a creative blendof primary sources, including testimonies from ex-Mau Mau participants, survey analysis, archival data, Mau Mau court cases, ceremonial reenactments, and folklore, The Power of the Oath demonstrates how and why the movement was spread, embraced, and internalized. Mwanzia Koster traces the evolution and structure of the Mau Mau oath, examining the British criminalization of the oath, its gendered use, and the purification associated with it, in order to reveal how Mau Mau unfolded in Kenya. Mickie Mwanzia Koster is associate professor of history at the University of Texas, Tyler.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNational liberation movementszKenya. 0aOathszKenya. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aModern History. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aHISTORY / Africa / East.2bisacsh  aBritish African relations.  aKikuyu war.  aMau Mau oath criminalization.  aMau Mau oath.  aMau Mau rebellion.  ahistory of Kenya.  ainternational relations.  anationalism.  awar history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782046523?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782046523423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782046523/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles